        "subtopic": "English Overview",
        "content": "• India’s journey into space science began in 1962 with INCOSPAR, founded by Dr. Vikram Sarabhai and Dr. Ramanathan.\n• In 1969, ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation) was established as the cornerstone of India’s space program.\n• Today, ISRO manages over 45 space research centres across India, focusing on satellite missions, rocket development, propulsion systems, navigation, communication, and remote sensing.\n• Achievements include Chandrayaan, Mangalyaan, Gaganyaan mission (in progress), and the globally renowned PSLV launch program.\n• India is now among the top global space powers, using space technology for national development and international collaborations."
